This is an interview with Dr. Mark Troy by Marshall McInnes on May the 11th, 1993 at Texas A&M University concerning his days in college, the Peace Corps, and his feelings about the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I am asking you to donate this tape to me or the Texas A&M oral history collection in the university archives.
Is that all right with you?
That's fine.
What is your full name?
Mark Edward Troy.
And when and where were you born?
St. Louis, Missouri, February 22, 1947.
And what is your education?
I have a doctorate in psychology from the University of Hawaii.
Now we'll get into some of the interview questions.
What year did you enter college, and where did you go to school?
I entered college in 1965.
I entered a seminary in 1965.
I was in there for a year and a half.
In January 1967, I entered Quincy College in Quincy, Illinois.
All right, describe the college in terms of its size, the attitudes of the students and faculty, and just the general air about the campus at the time you entered the college at Quincy.
Quincy College?
All right, Quincy was a small Catholic liberal arts college at that time.
It had about 2,000 students.
Some of the faculty were Franciscan priests.
Some of them were laypersons.
students were kind of a mix of students in terms of social attitudes.
Some of them were fairly conservative, others were fairly liberal.
They kind of spanned the whole spectrum.
Since it was a Catholic co-ed college, you tended to have students who were fairly religious in some ways.
If you weren't somehow religiously oriented, it wasn't too likely that you'd go there.
We didn't have fraternities or sororities, but we did have service organizations, which were fairly
fairly popular.
Were there any demonstrations on campus during the time you were there?
If there were, what kinds and over what?
There were several demonstrations, but they weren't sit-in type demonstrations or anything like that.
There was one vigil I remember for
for peace.
There was some concern, some unrest, I guess, shortly after the Democratic National Convention in 1968.
A lot of students were angry about that.
Some of the other protests mainly, I guess,
Just large groups of people meeting in front of the residence halls concerned more the hours and some of the restrictions on the residence halls than anything else.
And what did you do after you left Quincy?
Excuse me a second.
After Quincy, I went to Washington University in St. Louis to get a master's degree.
And after that, after getting my master's degree, I joined the Peace Corps.
Were you ever considering volunteering for service in the United States Armed Services?
And how did you feel about the lottery once it was established?
OK, and those are a couple questions, actually.
Service in the Armed Services.
Yeah, in fact, I did volunteer.
I did pretty much what?
What Bill Clinton did, when I went to graduate school, I signed up for ROTC.
And the problem was that it was easier to get into ROTC than it was to get into graduate school.
And it's the one that came down to actually making the commitment, going to summer camp

officers candidate school training between graduation and Washington U. I still hadn't been accepted at Washington U. I hadn't been accepted anywhere, and so I couldn't accept the officers candidate school thing.
I had to decline that.
So that was the one
consideration I had with volunteering.
Then when I did finally get accepted into Washington U, it was too late and I could not get back into OCS.
The summer was over, the summer training was over, and Washington U's ROTC was already filled.
The lottery, well, that was the one thing that
got me out of the draft, I was fairly happy for that.
Because I had one whole semester in graduate school where the concern about the draft was a problem.
I was already engaged, I wanted to stay in graduate school, but I was also
eligible for the draft.
I was classified 1A and I made it into the lottery just at the time that all my appeals had run out.
What were the attitudes of the students and professors at Washington when you entered?
Well, Washington U was fairly liberal in terms of
its politics.
It was among the universities in the St. Louis area and probably in the Midwest, it's probably the most liberal in its outlook.

Although you still have fairly conservative professors there, but for the most part you also had a large number of very liberal professors and the students that went there tended to be fairly liberal.
Even though they did have
in ROTC on campus, and students did participate in that.
Well, it filled up all the slots.
For the most part, I would say the students were very liberal.
Did you participate in any campus activities, protests, demonstrations at Washington?
Yeah, after Kent State
I participated in a number of demonstrations there.
There were some demonstrations at Washington U prior to Kent State.
One was around the ROTC building.
I didn't participate in that.
I didn't really think that that was right.
I didn't see anything wrong with students being in ROTC.
the Kent State protests and particularly after the incursion into Cambodia and everything.
I was opposed to the war and I didn't like the actions of the National Guard after Kent or the incursion into Cambodia.
So, Washington, you actually
was one of the universities that went on strike and shut down, the students shut it down over the Kent State protests, and I took part in those.
Describe your initial feelings about the Vietnam War, specifically on America's involvement in the war.
Well, my initial feelings were that
I supported the war.
When I started hearing about the war in high school, I was primarily a supporter of the war.
I supported the domino theory and that sort of thing.
Actually, in high school I was a member of
group that supported Goldwater for Presidents in the 1964 campaign.
It was primarily because of his position on Vietnam.
Q How did your family feel about the war?
A My family, for the most part, was
opposed to the war.
It's hard to say when they began to be opposed to it.
My father was probably one of the first people I knew who was opposed to the war in Vietnam.
And I'm not sure exactly when he took that position.
I'm not sure exactly what his position
the Goldwater Johnson campaign was either, but at least among all the adults I knew he was the first person to be opposed to it.
Was there any specific incident which made you for or against the war in Vietnam?
I don't know that there was any
specific incident.
There were certain incidents I recall, and my opinions on it changed over time.
The first time that I really began to think deeply about the war was the battle, the Yad Drang battle.
And my first response to that, I remember this, was that
It was the first time North Vietnamese regulars were involved in the war.
And my response was, my God, that's unfair.
What are those guys doing in there?
Of course, their regular army were fighting our regular army, is the thing.
It seems silly now to call that unfair.
But at the time, it was.
And I was still leaning more towards supporting the war in Vietnam.
That was also the first time that I knew of anybody that was killed in Vietnam.
There was a brother, a friend of mine, who was killed in that particular battle, and so I had kind of mixed feelings.
But that also caused a lot of discussion among myself and my friends and all that about the war.
It became probably the main topic.
The next incident that I recall was another friend of mine who was killed.
This guy was a guy that was about two years ahead of me.
He was a seminarian.
We didn't have fish camp or anything like that.
But we did have guys from the older classes who would make it their responsibility to
take care of the freshmen and so on when they came in.
And he was one of those guys.
And so he was a real good friend and everything.
He decided at some point that he didn't want to be a priest and left the seminary.
And generally, that meant that he got drafted before he could do anything else.
And so he was killed about five days after getting to Vietnam.
And it was one of those incidents we, a couple friends of mine and I went out.
We were watching a movie.
We were watching a documentary on Vietnam.
We came back.
I think we came back to my house.
And the phone just started ringing off the hook because the news had come out that this guy had gotten killed.
So all of us were just calling each other and everything.
It was one of those times when you really start to feel angry.
And that probably changed me a lot, although by that time I think I had become opposed to it and talked to a lot of people and everything and was opposed to the involvement.
But that was an incident that made me real angry about it.
When did you leave Washington and what did you do after you left?
I left Washington U at the beginning of 1972 to join the Peace Corps.
Alright, and where did you go in the Peace Corps?
I was in Thailand.
And where were you located in Thailand?
The first spot was a location
sort of in the north central area called Pits on the Loak.
And did you go by yourself or did someone else go with you?
Well, my wife went with me.
We were married at the time.
Were there any signs of the Vietnam War where you were located in Thailand?
Yeah, we had a lot of indications all over Thailand.
Thailand was...
both major R&R area for soldiers from Vietnam, and there were also a lot of bases there, active bases, most of them air bases that were involved in bombing.
Where we were actually located was not considered a military town, but the
The Thai Army had a headquarters there.
I can't remember which army.
I think it was the Thai 4th Army, but I'm not certain about that.
And so associated with that was a group of advisors.
I think there were probably about a dozen in the unit.
It was called JUSMAC, Joint U.S. Military Advisory Command.
It was either JUSMAC for command or JUSMAG for group, and I think they used both terms.
They were primarily officers.
I don't think that there were...
any enlisted men, mainly officers, and their headquarters was not too far from us, just a few blocks actually, and so we'd see them all the time.
They were friendly guys.
We'd go sit around and talk with them a lot, just to kind of get an idea of what was going on and everything.
There was also a radar station there that was an installation used by the planes leaving some of the other military bases heading towards Vietnam.
How did you feel about the war once you reached Thailand?
Did your feelings change?
Funny thing, in a lot of ways my feelings were in response to the Thais' feelings about the war.
The Thais were very supportive of the war in Vietnam, at least the Thai government was.
And one of the problems was that the government was, for the most part when we were there, was a fairly oppressive military government.
Well, I shouldn't say it was fairly oppressive.
It was a military government.
Maybe in terms of dictatorships, it was less oppressive than some of the others that we're familiar with.
But still, they ran the country in what I considered an oppressive type of manner.
There was not a lot of free thought, speech, movement, that sort of thing.
And a lot of the people, Thais themselves, tend to like that.
It's not that they were really chafing under this type of government.
They like strong leaders.
They have a monarchy and have always had a monarchy.
And they like the fact that their military leaders are
are strong.
What I would hear from Thais when I talked to them was that they liked Nixon because Nixon seemed like a powerful figure to them.
And so I'd get into conversations and I would try to tell them on my side that I thought that the law was wrong and that I didn't like the things he was doing to their country.
small cities of prostitutes building up around the air bases.
You had rampant inflation.
You had all sorts of problems that seemed like they were the result of the military presence being in Thailand.
funny thing happened.
After Saigon fell, the Thais did very much of an about-face, and this strain of anti-Americanism developed.
So I found myself on the other side now.
They were saying many of the things that I'd been saying before, but now I found myself defending much of the
American position in the world and the response to communism.
So in many ways it was, I did do a complete about-face, but I adjusted my positions a little bit.
I took a more moderate position, I guess.
in response to more radical Thai positions at that point.
What did the soldiers that you talked to in Thailand, how did they feel about the war, the advisor group?
Well, they were professional soldiers.
They were there because the military was their career and they were
strongly supportive of the U.S. involvement.
So our discussions there tended to be more, well,
Basically, we pretty much knew each other's position and so we didn't get into heated debates about it.
About the only time that we did get into debates was, and this wasn't even a real debate, but it was just a little discussion, was in the Nixon-McGovern election in 72.
to file an absentee ballot, we had to take it over to the commander of the base to get it authorized.
You know, he had to sign it in, and so we got into a little discussion then.
He said that his vote would cancel one of our votes, and so then we started talking about, you know, the various positions in the election.
Would you like to describe your involvement within the student movement while you were at college and elaborate on some of the things that you did that you felt that were important in the movement?
Well, most of my involvement was when I was at Washington U. Quincy College wasn't terribly involved in
in large-scale protests, partly because it was a small college and the town itself was a fairly conservative community.
On the other hand, the faculty, in many ways, were willing to go along with the protests.
They were present at one protest vigil we had and everything like that.
At Washington U, it was a lot different.
is located right in St. Louis.
It draws students from all over the world.
Like I said, they're fairly liberal.
There's a whole community around Washington U, even though St. Louis itself is a fairly conservative city.
The community that surrounds Washington U is itself very liberal, and so there were quite a number of
organizers on campus, student organizers, and many of them were involved in the strike after the Kent State incident.
And so there were rallies all the time.
In fact, it was very exciting.
The Washington U is designed as one of these real old universities with all the buildings surrounding the quadrangle.
which is the central focus of the university.
And so you'd go to Washington U, and you'd walk through the Quadrangle, and there would just be all these people there holding rallies and speakers set up.
A lot of activists came to the university, nationally known activists.
Some were on the faculty.
Barry Comner, who was an environmental activist, was on the faculty.
And of course, the environmental activists also got involved in the peace movement and so on.
Many of the faculty were involved in that.
David Harris, Joan Baez's husband, ex-husband, came to the campus I think at least once and spoke.
So I was involved in a lot of marches, a lot of protests, a lot of demonstrations.
One of the things that happened during the strike was that they attempted to coordinate it with all the other universities to coordinate the activities.
They wanted to shut down universities all across the country.
They wanted to have all sorts of demonstrations planned in all the cities.
So I was involved with one of the committees at Washington U that was coordinating that, actually.
There were a lot of committees.
And my only real act of civil disobedience in that whole thing was I needed to contact one other university and didn't have any money to do it.
I called up a radio station that was billed as an outlaw radio station and asked them if they had a phone number that I could use, a credit card number that I could charge.
I guess probably not a credit card, but a number that I could charge a call to.
And they gave me a number.
And when I asked who it was, they said it was the White House's number.
and that I should just use Nixon's name.
So I did.
I placed a call and said I wanted to charge it to this number.
And they asked, well, who do I charge it to?
And I said to charge it to RM Nixon, N-I-X-O-N. And they accepted the call without question.
I have no idea if that was actually his number.
But at least I got the call through.
I think it went to Brown University or someplace like that.
But that was my only thing with civil disobedience.
The other people I was involved with during the protest movement were people like the American Friends Service Committee, the Quakers, basically, who were pacifists.
I wasn't a pacifist, but I did go to them for draft counseling.
The interesting thing about that was that
They gave me a list of procedures to follow in constructing and making an appeal to appeal my draft status.
And the idea was that you, according to the law, you had to have your appeal within this X number of days and so on.
And the boards met on specific days.
And you could buy time by counting the days and then hand-carrying your appeal in.
You waited until you had 30 days, and I think the board met once a month.

So once I got the notice and I counted the days and found out when the next board meeting was going to be held, and I'd go in and deliver my appeal after that board meeting because then they couldn't consider that appeal until the next board meeting and so on and so on.
Instead of 30 days, I'd get 60 days on it and so on.
The American Defense Service Committee worked all that out for me.
But the interesting thing about that was that my draft board were kind of cool guys.
I don't know how other people's draft boards were, but I went to my first meeting with the draft board, my appeal hearing.
You had to request a personal appearance before the draft board.
That was one of the first steps.
So I went to them.
and requested an appeal on the basis of being a graduate student.
They denied it, but they also said, but now these are the next steps you can take.
And they were exactly the same steps that the American Friends Service Committee had told me to take.
It was just count the days, and this is when we're going to meet, and so you bring in the letter afterwards and all that, which kind of floored me that
They were giving me all that appeal information.
Then my next contact with the draft board was when we went to Thailand.
Even though I had a high number in the lottery, I was still eligible for the draft.
I was still classified as 1A status.
In actual fact, I was out of the draft.
Technically, I wasn't.
So I had to get permission from my draft board.
So I went to the draft board to get the paperwork done, get all the permission.
A woman asked me where I was going.
I said, well, I'm going to Thailand.
And she said, we've been trying all these years to keep you guys out of there, and now you want to go?
And I said, well, yeah, that's right.
Which I thought was kind of a...
cool thing for them to do, too.
I love.
Every night and every day.
Yes, I love you for all the wrong reasons.
Cause you love me in all the right ways.
